  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 광성자(廣成子) : '
    value: 황제(黃帝) 때의 신선이다. 공동산(崆峒山)의 석실(石室)에 은거하였으며, 황제가 일찍이 지극한 도의 요체를 물었다 한다.
english:
  title: A Record of the Dwelling of Leisure
  author: Lim Chun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The truly hidden sage possesses the power to manifest, and the truly manifest sage possesses the power to hide. Those who despise office and scorn riches, who pillow their heads on white stones and rinse their teeth in clear streams—they merely seek obscurity and pursue eccentricity. Do they possess the capacity to manifest? Those shackled by reputation, mired in the marketplace with official caps upon their heads and seals at their waists—they merely chase power and pursue profit. Do they possess the capacity to hide?

    Only one who neither blindly conforms nor blindly rebels, who withdraws when the time calls for withdrawal and advances when the time calls for advancement—not as a second-rate sage but as one equal to the ancient worthies—such a one knows both rising and falling, both coming and going, and finds himself ever satisfied. This is the truly hidden who remains hidden, the truly manifest who remains manifest. When hidden, the Way is preserved with him; when manifest, the Way moves through him.

    In this world, among those scholars possessed of the Way, only one man embodies this teaching perfectly: our nation's Minister Lee. His name was Chung-rya, his courtesy name Cha-chen. His inner nature housed heaven itself, while outwardly he dwelt among men—such was his Way. Golden halls and jade chambers were his dwelling, the purple palaces and cinnabar terraces his offices. His lineage descended from the royal house of Kyongju, and for seven generations his family had produced masters of letters. His mother, Lady Lee, dreamed of a yellow-robed figure and thus conceived him. From childhood, therefore, he delighted in reading the Taoist canon and devoted himself to the Taoist path, having surely cultivated these practices in a former life.

    He always kept his heart beyond material things, casting off all fetters and restraints. He abandoned his home and withdrew to Mount Kaya, where he took the name Azure Rosy Clouds. His father, fearing he could not dissuade his son's determination to renounce the world, sought out the hermit Eun Weon-chung and the monk Ik-jong, both versed in secret arts. He sent them word, and they conspired together: "Among all the mountains of the south, none surpasses Moon-birth Peak in Tao-kang—where earth's dragon-forms sweep toward heaven's throne. One dwelling here must soon receive the imperial summons."

    They cleared the land and built a retreat, then invited the master with these words: "This mountain possesses Taoist energy. Only an extraordinary person could answer its call. Would you not make this your dwelling place for cultivating immortality?" Unaware of their scheme, he gladly accepted.

    Upon arrival, he named his hermitage the Dwelling of Leisure. To its north rose a small peak, verdant and towering—Jade Lightning Summit. Each day he would climb to its crown in his plain robes, sitting in meditation through the hours like a cicada clinging to a leaf or a turtle with eyes sealed shut. To his left lay the Yellow Court Classic, to his right his zither. When he played, the notes would echo through the forests, causing woodcutters to believe they had glimpsed an immortal. Even now his traces remain. When mist clears and rain passes, the crystalline echoes return as though sounding in the ear itself.

    He was prepared to transcend all worldly concerns, to refuse even the thrones of Yao and Shun, to regard as distant teachers the immortals of the Eastern Grove, the Recluse Tao, and the Celestial Master Zhang. He would govern the transformations of creation itself, harmonize with the celestial mechanism, inhale the primal breath of noon, and contemplate ascension to the azure empyrean. When his practice reached perfection and his deeds were complete, mounting a dragon-drawn carriage, he would ascend before the Jade Emperor himself—thus did I perceive how he dwelt hidden, achieving true concealment.

    Yet he also possessed medical knowledge, believing that healing could benefit the multitude. He studied the art profoundly, becoming expert as any master, and saved countless lives. When a county magistrate suffered from paralysis, the master treated him with needles, and he recovered instantly. Later, when the Sovereign fell ill, the magistrate recommended him. The court summoned him, but before he could depart, the Dragon Carriage departed the earthly realm—he could not arrive in time.

    The Sage King, having heard his reputation in former times, summoned him to the palace and sought to bind him with official position and stipend. Yet the master now walked the boundary between engagement and withdrawal, his spirit remaining inwardly hidden even as his form appeared at court. But having emerged to answer the summons, he became as the Immortal Kuangcheng, one who broadcasts the refinement of the highest Way through the methods of governance, daily illuminating the eyes and ears of all people.

    Later he crossed the sea to Song, where he received direct transmission from the priests Huang Ta-chung and Zhou Yu-ling, penetrating fully the essential teachings and secret principles known to few. Upon returning to his homeland, he petitioned to establish a Taoist temple as a blessed place for national rituals and sacrifices—this is the present-day Temple of Blessing. He rang the great bell in the lecture hall and opened wide the gate to all mysteries. Those seeking the Way crowded his doorway like merchants at market, like stars circling the celestial river. Thus did I perceive him as dwelling with the Way in manifestation, achieving true emergence.

    His advance and retreat corresponded to the times, his rest in seclusion was like clouds rising from mountains to wander through vast emptiness, forming and dispersing without intention, bound by nothing. The sage's every action and stillness responds to the flourishing or decline of the age—how could he be constrained by the calculations of yin and yang? Those like Eun Weon-chung who boasted of their clever schemes to "hook" the master deserve no credence.

    A place of rare beauty must await a worthy person to reveal its excellence—without such a one, even sacred ground cannot manifest its destiny. Had the master not possessed his singular and transcendent character, that valley would have remained merely a haunt of tigers and foxes, a loss for both man and place. Whether he awaited this place or it awaited him, I cannot say. Yet it was so.

    After the master answered the imperial summons and departed, no successor dwelt there. Through long years it fell silent, gradually becoming waste. Cloud-shrouded mountains and mist-hung waters retained their sorrow for ages. In the twelfth year of King Ŭijong's reign, the master's son, now Minister Yi Yun-su, came to garrison Kŭmsŏng and at last sought out the place. The ancient altar remained, the old well stood—relics that seemed to mourn, to yearn, to lament their ruin.

    Moved by this sight, the Minister conceived the desire to restore it. He expended his stipend for workers, gathered materials from the forests, cleared the overgrowth, and built an order hall. All furnishings—bells, stones, tables, every implement of reverence—were completed. When the work finished, he reported it to the throne. The king approved and specially bestowed a painting of Avalokitesvara, along with fifteen hundred acres of fertile land. Moreover, the Minister set aside one hundred measures of grain, employing the self-replenishing method so that annual proceeds would forever sustain the temple. He appointed virtuous monks to oversee the place.

    Thus did this hidden realm, through meeting the master, come suddenly into splendor. Barren cliffs now glow with beauty, dark ravines shine with light. Its name will endure a thousand years—is this not a place made wondrous by the worthiness of men?

    Alas, though I never served in his presence with broom in hand, once I beheld his portrait in the Minister's home. Straightening my cap and wiping my eyes, I gazed upon it: clear in countenance, refined in bearing, like spring dew glistening on morning gold. Contemplating his life's deeds, one's heart forgets all pettiness and greed. Why need I have glimpsed the visage of the immortals of old? My only sorrow is that destiny granted me shallow roots in the celestial realm and weak cultivation in the Taoist way. I could not grasp the vines and part the clouds, knock once at the immortal gate, glimpse the smoking furnace or rest in the shade of the sacred grove. In sorrow and longing, I can only gaze upward—thus I have composed this song:

    *The master departs, leading the azure dragon,*
    *Mounting the shoulders of the pine-dwelling sage, hidden in sacred heights.*
    *The master arrives, riding the jade-colored qilin,*
    *The heavens display their signs before the purple throne.*
    *Beyond the eight extremes, wandering in vastness,*
    *Entering the Eastern Sea, he returns no more.*
    *The ancient grotto lies in silence,*
    *While the long day sees the phoenix sleep.*

    Once I paid respects to the Minister and took my place among his learned guests. The Minister turned to me and said: "My father's remarkable deeds have long gone unrecorded. It seems fate has brought you here. Would you not set them down?"

    I demurred, claiming my writing was unfit for such purposes, but he pressed me repeatedly. Thus I accepted the commission. I have recorded the founding dates and sketched the broad outlines of his withdrawal and emergence. Regarding his official career and the chronology of his years, these are preserved in the official histories and require no further account.
  footnotes:
    - 'Kuangcheng: A legendary immortal who dwelt in a stone chamber during the reign of the Yellow Emperor. The Yellow Emperor is said to have once sought from him the essentials of the highest Way.'
    - 'Yao and Shun: Legendary sage-kings of ancient China, models of virtue and wisdom.'
    - 'The Dragon Carriage: A metaphor for imperial death or the passage of the sovereign.'
    - 'Avalokitesvara: The Bodhisattva of Compassion in East Asian Buddhism, often depicted in paintings presented by the court.'
    - 'The self-replenishing method (子母法): An economic system in which principal generates interest to be used in perpetuity for maintenance or charitable purposes.'
